or someone living in a scrubby area, from Old French <i>bro(u)ce</i> ‘thicket, brushwood’ (from Late Latin <i>bruscia</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in France named Brousse. Compare   Bruce   and   Brusse  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered form <i>Bruce</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]}]},{"name":"robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":30,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705183,"age":50,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705184,"age":60,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When robert De Brusse was born in 1036, his father, ragnvald bruesson II, was 25 and his mother, ariogia countess of orkney, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Emma de brittany. He died in 1098, in England, at the age of 62."},"et":{"1036–1098":"1036–1098","1034–1094":"1034–1094","1034–1066":"1034–1066","1049–1095":"1049–1095","–1094":"–1094","1011–1046":"1011–1046","1015–Female":"1015–Surnud","after 1095":"pärast 1095","1066":"1066","1011":"1011","1098":"1098","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1094":"1094","1049":"1049","1015":"1015","1036":"1036","1046":"1046","1034":"1034","England":"England","Scotland":"Scotland","Briouze, Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Briouze, Orne, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Bramber, Sussex, England":"Bramber, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1036–1098":"1036–1098","1034–1094":"1034–1094","1034–1066":"1034–1066","1049–1095":"1049–1095","–1094":"–1094","1011–1046":"1011–1046","1015–Female":"1015–Kuollut","after 1095":"1095 jälkeen","1066":"1066","1011":"1011","1098":"1098","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1094":"